snippet: The accident at the factory, which made sneakers for the Japanese manufacturer Asics, reinforced global worries about factory safety in poor countries.
abstract: Storage area collapses at footwear factory in Tream Tbal, Cambodia, killing at least two workers and injuring dozen more; incident, coming on heels of factory collapse in Bangladesh, underlines global worries about factory safety in poor countries.

byline.original: By THOMAS FULLER and KEITH BRADSHER
byline.contributor: Thomas Fuller reported from Tream Tbal, Cambodia, and Keith Bradsher from Hong Kong. Poypiti Amatatham contributed reporting from Phnom Penh, Cambodia, and Hiroko Tabuchi from Tokyo.

lead_paragraph: The accident at the factory, which made sneakers for the Japanese manufacturer Asics, reinforced global worries about factory safety in poor countries.

headline.seo: Deadly Collapse in Cambodia Renews Safety Concerns
